INSERT INTO `email_queue` VALUES ('1', '2023-07-04 16:58:03', '2023-07-04 16:58:08', '1', 'jmejia@cimat.mx', '[CIMPS 2023] Submissions have been assigned for review', 'Dear CIMPS 2023 Reviewer,\n\nThank you for signing up to review submissions submitted to CIMPS 2023.  It is now time for the review process to begin and submission assignments have been made.  Using the username and password you created when you registered to be a reviewer, you will find the submissions assigned to you by going to http://www.cimps.org, selecting OpenConf, and signing in under Committee Members.  This will display the list of submissions you have been assigned to review.  Clicking on the submission title will bring up the online review form and clicking on the file symbol to the right of the submission title will bring up a copy of the file.  You may reopen and modify or amend previously submitted reviews.\n\nDEADLINE:JULY 28, 2023.\n\nIf you do not remember your username and password, features are available to let you reset them if you still remember the email address you specified when filling out the reviewer registration form.\n\nAs much as possible we tried to assign submissions that we think will interest you.  We apologize in advance if you are not interested or knowledgeable about the topic areas you were assigned.  If you will not be able to review a submission, please inform us IMMEDIATELY so we can reassign the submission to someone else.\n\nREMINDER: By reviewing unpublished submissions, you are accepting the ethical responsibility not to disclose their contents to anyone else.\n\nIf we assigned you your own submission or a submission for which you have a conflict of interest, let us know and we will reassign you!\n\nPlease complete these reviews as soon as possible. \n\nThanks again for helping make International Conference on Software Process Improvement 2023 - CIMPS 2023 a success!\n\nCIMPS 2023 Program Chair\nadmin@cimps-submission.com', '31');
INSERT INTO `email_queue` VALUES ('2', '2023-07-04 17:00:28', '2023-07-04 17:00:34', '1', 'jmejia@cimat.mx', '[CIMPS 2023] Submissions have been assigned for review', 'Dear CIMPS 2023 Reviewer,\n\nThank you for signing up to review submissions submitted to CIMPS 2023.  It is now time for the review process to begin and submission assignments have been made.  Using the username and password you created when you registered to be a reviewer, you will find the submissions assigned to you by going to https://cimps-submission.com/openconf/review/signin.php , selecting OpenConf, and signing in under Committee Members.  This will display the list of submissions you have been assigned to review.  Clicking on the submission title will bring up the online review form and clicking on the file symbol to the right of the submission title will bring up a copy of the file.  You may reopen and modify or amend previously submitted reviews.\n\nDEADLINE:JULY 28, 2023.\n\nIf you do not remember your username and password, features are available to let you reset them if you still remember the email address you specified when filling out the reviewer registration form.\n\nAs much as possible we tried to assign submissions that we think will interest you.  We apologize in advance if you are not interested or knowledgeable about the topic areas you were assigned.  If you will not be able to review a submission, please inform us IMMEDIATELY so we can reassign the submission to someone else.\n\nREMINDER: By reviewing unpublished submissions, you are accepting the ethical responsibility not to disclose their contents to anyone else.\n\nIf we assigned you your own submission or a submission for which you have a conflict of interest, let us know and we will reassign you!\n\nPlease complete these reviews as soon as possible. \n\nThanks again for helping make International Conference on Software Process Improvement 2023 - CIMPS 2023 a success!\n\nCIMPS 2023 Program Chair\nadmin@cimps-submission.com', '31');
INSERT INTO `email_queue` VALUES ('3', '2023-07-26 02:05:58', '2023-07-26 02:06:03', '1', 'sergio.galvan@cimat.mx', '[CIMPS 2023] Your submission has been accepted!', 'On behalf of the International Conference on Software Process Improvement 2023 - CIMPS 2023, I am pleased to inform you that your submission, titled\n\nState of Art of DevOps: concepts, challenges, tools\n\nhas been accepted.  \n\nWe have included the reviewers\' feedback at the end of this message.\n\nCongratulations,\n  Program Committee, CIMPS 2023\n  admin@cimps-submission.com\n\n\n***************************************************************\n\nAUTHOR COMMENTS: The manuscript aims to provide an understanding of a set of open-source tools to use in each activity of the DevOps processes. Moreover, the manuscript highlights key concepts and current challenges in this area. After a careful review of the manuscript, I found three major issues that must be addressed before its publication.   \n\n1. It is highly recommended that a native english speaker review the manuscript.\n2. A lack of methodological support is present in the manuscript. It means, a scientific paper must be always supported by a formal method and/or methodology to conduct, in this case, a literature review. Without this, the manuscript is providing subjective opinions about a topic.\n3. There is a lot of studies that have provided a solid basis that has helped practitioners to understand the benefits, concepts, tools and challenges related to DevOps. In this regard, I did not find a new contibution in the manuscript. Furthermore, without a method, it is too difficult to valorate the findings presented in the manuscript. I strongly suggest to review the following studies in order to improve the authors\' contribution:\n- Jabbari, R., bin Ali, N., Petersen, K., & Tanveer, B. (2016, May). What is DevOps? A systematic mapping study on definitions and practices. In Proceedings of the scientific workshop proceedings of XP2016 (pp. 1-11).\n- Zhu, L., Bass, L., & Champlin-Scharff, G. (2016). DevOps and its practices. IEEE software, 33(3), 32-34.\n- Bou Ghantous, G., & Gill, A. (2017). DevOps: Concepts, practices, tools, benefits and challenges. PACIS2017.\n- Senapathi, M., Buchan, J., & Osman, H. (2018, June). DevOps capabilities, practices, and challenges: Insights from a case study. In Proceedings of the 22nd International Conference on Evaluation and Assessment in Software Engineering 2018 (pp. 57-67).\n- Leite, L., Rocha, C., Kon, F., Milojicic, D., & Meirelles, P. (2019). A survey of DevOps concepts and challenges. ACM Computing Surveys (CSUR), 52(6), 1-35.\n- Gokarna, M., & Singh, R. (2021, February). DevOps: a historical review and future works. In 2021 International Conference on Computing, Communication, and Intelligent Systems (ICCCIS) (pp. 366-371). IEEE.\n\n\n\n***************************************************************\n\nAUTHOR COMMENTS: The study investigates an interesting subject.  The research discusses several definitions of DevOps and provides us with tables listing tools organized into groups with a variety of notable features.\nSince the study doesn\'t specify how the tool list was compiled, it would be helpful to have that information up front. \nAnd secondly, to learn the methodology used to classify tools into different sets. Assigning the tools to their appropriate groups is a challenge. Given its features (advantages are listed in the study), a tool might fit into more than one classification. \nAs an illustration, consider the fact that the criteria by which the graphic design tool Inkscape is assigned to the planning activity are not defined.\nIt is suggested that the allocation procedure be explained in greater detail. Second, solve the integration issue so that a series of tools can communicate with one another.\n\n\n\n***************************************************************\n\nAUTHOR COMMENTS: Summary\nThe paper presents a survey of open source tools to support Dev Ops\n\nPoints for\n\n•	The research is timely and of practical importance  to the field.\n\nOpportunities for improvements\n\n•	The methodology is not well defined.\n•	Background sections are treated at textbook level. There is no indication of similar research \n•	Tools are presented quite sucintevely and there is little to no recommendation nor discussion. As a practitioner, after reading your paper, I am not sure If the content can help me select a tool\n\nGeneral comments\n\n•	What do you understand by Open Source? I believe you should delve in this concept. And merge it with licensing permission.  Non-derivative the same as attribution?\n•	Focus on improving the methodology, improve your criteria, and maybe create an ideal cycle, can all tools attain this cycle?\n\n\n\n', '1223');
